---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Hero from '../components/Hero.astro';
import KpiStrip from '../components/KpiStrip.astro';
import Section from '../components/Section.astro';
import Formula from '../components/Formula.astro';

const kpis = [
  { label: 'Evaluation horizon', value: '25', unit: 'years', note: 'Full lifecycle analysis period' },
  { label: 'Optimisation objectives', value: '2', unit: 'criteria', note: 'Maximise NPV · minimise CO₂' },
  { label: 'Weighting factor λ', value: '0→1', unit: '', note: 'Cost-only to emissions-only' },
  { label: 'Key outputs', value: '3', unit: 'metrics', note: 'NPV · payback · CO₂ abatement' },
];
---

<Base title="Chapter 6 · Carbon Reduction Calculator">

  <Hero
    eyebrow="Chapter 06"
    title="Carbon<br/>Reduction<br/>Calculator"
    subtitle="Built for municipalities exploring green energy investments before committing to them."
    image="/oberaegeri-zg.jpg"
    imageAlt="Oberägeri, Canton Zug"
  />

  <div class="container">
    <p class="lead reveal">
      Municipalities considering green energy investments face a common challenge: will the investment actually pay off, and how much CO₂ can realistically be reduced? This calculator was built to answer exactly that. It gives municipal decision-makers a tool to interactively experiment with rooftop photovoltaic (PV) and solar-thermal (ST) scenarios, before any decisions are made or installations are underway. The tool is interactive because each user can adjust the available roof area and energy prices, which the tool uses to calculate projected CO₂ savings, annual cost reduction, the payback period and the net present value for their specific building and budget.
    </p>
    <p class="lead-sub reveal">
      Our calculator can mathematically transform data from any Swiss town hall into an interactive what-if model. The sections below explain each step of the calculation.
    </p>
    <div class="use-case-box reveal">
      <span class="use-case-label">Practical use case</span>
      <p>For municipalities that have already received a contractor quote during the budgeting phase, the quoted investment costs can be included in the calculator. The rates must be provided in square metres but when included they help calculate the financial viability of the quoted PV/ST split. The tool computes the NPV for each scenario and highlights whether a different allocation of roof area would deliver a better return or greater CO₂ reduction. The results and calculator can be used to challenge an offer, compare alternatives, or build the business case for your municipal council.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="lead-cta reveal">
      <a class="cta-btn" href="https://som-calculator.vercel.app" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open calculator ↗</a>
    </div>

    <KpiStrip kpis={kpis} />
  </div>

  <Section chip="06 / A" label="A · Data Sources" title="Data Sources &amp; Methodology" id="s-6-a">
    <p>The calculator utilises assumptions based on baseline consumption for a single municipality. For Oberägeri, the standard figures for electricity and heat demand are pre-loaded, and they come from audited consumption data and operational details provided via email correspondence with Alexander Klauz, administrative director of the Oberägeri municipality (Klauz, 2026). The data reflects the town hall's 2025 energy records, including the WWZ WasserSonneStrom tariff mix (80 % hydropower, 20 % PV) and the wood-chip district heating supply.</p>
    <p>The emission factors were drawn predominantly from KBOB (<em>Ökobilanzdaten im Baubereich</em> (2009/1:2022, version 8.02)), which is the Swiss federal reference dataset for life-cycle assessment in the building sector (KBOB, 2022). If a local supplier publishes its own verified figures, such as the WWZ WasserSonneStrom mix, these take precedence over the national averages. Every factor used in the model can be inspected and, if needed, overridden.</p>
  </Section>

  <Section chip="06 / B" label="B · Inputs" title="What You Enter" id="s-6-b">
    <p>The tool is built around a simple principle: the user only has to enter the data available to them. For example, electricity and heat consumption from a prior year, the utilised heating method, the utilised electricity mix, and the available roof area for a PV and ST upgrade.</p>
    <p>Optionally, the user can refine the financially relevant data points. For example, the user can adjust the model to reflect their actual electricity price and set an investment budget. When a budget is defined, the calculator uses it to calculate an optimised PV/ST split based on the financial constraints. Additionally, a weighting factor informs the model of the relative importance of CO₂ savings versus cost savings. Finally, the NPV calculation can be adjusted to include an inflation factor and the user can specify the rate of system degradation over time within a chosen depreciation period.</p>
  </Section>

  <Section chip="06 / C" label="C · Expert settings" title="Defaults &amp; Expert Settings" id="s-6-c">
    <p>Using the calculator in its most user-friendly form requires no further data adjustments other than those listed above, as each default assumption has been set based on generalisable averages. For users that want more influence over the model there is an expert panel that allows them to adjust electricity and heat emission factors, installation cost rates, maintenance costs, specific energy yields, and embodied emissions of the solar panels. When not adjusted, the values are based predominantly on the KBOB dataset or published Swiss LCA sources (KBOB, 2022). The baseline estimates for the annual maintenance costs of PV and solar thermal rest on the operating cost figures published by EnergieSchweiz/BFE (2017) and the U.S. Department of Energy (n.d.). Edit them only if you have site-specific figures for example from a contractor's quote or a supplier's environmental product declaration.</p>
  </Section>

  <Section chip="06 / D" label="D · The Model" title="The Model" id="s-6-d">
    <p>The optimisation model developed for the town hall is designed as a <strong>multi-criteria optimisation problem</strong>. The goal of the solver is to determine the optimal system configuration and the ideal ratio between photovoltaic and solar thermal panels on the roof. The algorithm optimises a mathematical objective function composed of two competing primary objectives over a <strong>25-year time horizon</strong>: maximising the net present value (NPV) and minimising the building's total greenhouse gas emissions.</p>
    <p>To allow mathematical control of these objectives, the model includes a <strong>variable weighting factor w</strong> (0 ≤ w ≤ 1) that determines whether the solver calculates a purely cost-optimised solution, a purely emissions-minimised solution, or a balanced compromise. The combined objective function Z minimised by the solver is:</p>
    <Formula label="Objective function">
      <code>min Z = w · (1 − NPV / K_Baseline,Total) + (1 − w) · (E_Scenario,Total / E_Baseline,Total)</code>
    </Formula>
    <div class="var-list">
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">Z</span><span class="var-desc">Total value of the objective function minimised by the solver</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">w</span><span class="var-desc">Weighting factor, freely chosen (0 = emissions only, 1 = cost only)</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">NPV</span><span class="var-desc">= K_Baseline,Total − K_Scenario,Total · Financial value added over N years vs. the baseline</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">K_Baseline,Total</span><span class="var-desc">Total energy costs under current conditions (baseline) over N years</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">E_Scenario,Total</span><span class="var-desc">Total CO₂eq emissions of the scenario over N years</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">E_Baseline,Total</span><span class="var-desc">Total CO₂eq emissions under current conditions (baseline) over N years</span></div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section chip="06 / E" label="E · Variables" title="Decision Variables and Constraints" id="s-6-e">
    <p>The key decision variables in the model are the installed areas of the two solar technologies:</p>
    <div class="var-list">
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">x</span><span class="var-desc">Area of the photovoltaic system (m²)</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">y</span><span class="var-desc">Area of the solar thermal system (m²)</span></div>
    </div>
    <p>The solver determines how much of the available roof area to allocate to each technology. Three constraints always apply:</p>
    <Formula label="Roof area constraint">
      <code>x + y ≤ A_Limit</code>
    </Formula>
    <Formula label="Non-negativity">
      <code>x ≥ 0 ,  y ≥ 0</code>
    </Formula>
    <Formula label="ST sizing limit prevents oversizing relative to heat demand">
      <code>y · q_ST ≤ Q_current</code>
    </Formula>
    <p>Here <em>A_Limit</em> is the maximum roof area available, <em>q_ST</em> is the specific annual solar thermal yield per m², and <em>Q_current</em> is the current annual heat demand. All energy flows are additionally bounded between 0 and 1 so that no negative residual demands can arise. If the budget constraint is activated, the following also applies:</p>
    <Formula label="Budget constraint">
      <code>Inv_PV · x + Inv_ST · y + K_Batt ≤ Budget</code>
    </Formula>
    <div class="var-list">
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">Inv_PV</span><span class="var-desc">Investment cost in CHF per m² of photovoltaic system</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">Inv_ST</span><span class="var-desc">Investment cost in CHF per m² of solar thermal system</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">K_Batt</span><span class="var-desc">Battery cost in CHF (only counted if battery option is enabled)</span></div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section chip="06 / F" label="F · Baseline" title="Baseline Functions" id="s-6-f">
    <p>The baseline functions describe the reference state of the town hall without any additional PV or solar thermal systems. They serve as the comparison basis for the economic and environmental assessment of optimised scenarios, accounting for current electricity and heat demand, the respective energy prices, and associated emission factors.</p>
    <p>The annual baseline cost in year <em>t</em> is:</p>
    <Formula label="Annual baseline cost">
      <code>K_Baseline,t = S_current · P_electricity,t + Q_current · P_heat,t + F_electricity,t</code>
    </Formula>
    <div class="var-list">
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">S_current</span><span class="var-desc">Current annual electricity consumption (kWh)</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">P_electricity,t</span><span class="var-desc">Electricity price in CHF/kWh in year t</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">Q_current</span><span class="var-desc">Current annual heat consumption (kWh)</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">P_heat,t</span><span class="var-desc">Heat price in CHF/kWh in year t</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">F_electricity,t</span><span class="var-desc">Fixed electricity charges in CHF in year t</span></div>
    </div>
    <p>The present value of total baseline costs over the full project duration:</p>
    <Formula label="Total present value of baseline costs">
      <code>K_Baseline,Total = Σ [ K_Baseline,t / (1 + i)^t ]  for t = 1…N</code>
    </Formula>
    <div class="var-list">
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">i</span><span class="var-desc">Discount factor</span></div>
    </div>
    <p>Annual baseline emissions:</p>
    <Formula label="Annual baseline emissions">
      <code>E_Baseline,t = S_current · EF_electricity + Q_current · EF_heat</code>
    </Formula>
    <div class="var-list">
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">EF_electricity</span><span class="var-desc">Electricity emission factor (kg CO₂/kWh)</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">EF_heat</span><span class="var-desc">Heat emission factor (kg CO₂/kWh)</span></div>
    </div>
    <p>Cumulative baseline emissions over the full evaluation period:</p>
    <Formula label="Cumulative baseline emissions">
      <code>E_Baseline,Total = Σ E_Baseline,t  for t = 1…N</code>
    </Formula>
  </Section>

  <Section chip="06 / G" label="G · Scenario" title="Scenario Functions" id="s-6-g">
    <p>The scenario functions describe the situation after the new systems have been installed. They calculate the remaining electricity and heat demand after self-generation via PV and solar thermal systems, and additionally account for feed-in revenues, maintenance costs, system emissions, and where applicable battery effects.</p>
    <p>Annual scenario cost in year <em>t</em>:</p>
    <Formula label="Annual scenario cost">
      <code>K_Scenario,t = F_electricity,t + S_res,t · P_electricity,t + H_res,t · P_heat,t
              + M_PV,t · x + M_ST,t · y − PV_export,t · P_feed-in,t</code>
    </Formula>
    <p>PV generation, self-consumption, and residual grid demand:</p>
    <Formula label="PV generation">
      <code>PV_t      = x · q_PV · f_PV(t)           where f_PV(t) = max(0, 1 − (t−1) · d_PV)</code><br/>
      <code>PV_self,t = min(PV_t · sc(x,t), S_current)  (on-site self-consumption)</code><br/>
      <code>PV_export,t = max(0, PV_t − PV_self,t)      (exported to grid)</code><br/>
      <code>S_res,t   = max(0, S_current − PV_self,t)   (residual grid demand)</code>
    </Formula>
    <div class="var-list">
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">q_PV</span><span class="var-desc">Specific annual PV yield, kWh/(m²·year)</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">d_PV</span><span class="var-desc">Annual PV degradation rate</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">sc(x,t)</span><span class="var-desc">Effective self-consumption share in year t (see section J)</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">P_feed-in,t</span><span class="var-desc">Feed-in tariff for exported PV electricity in CHF/kWh in year t</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">M_PV,t</span><span class="var-desc">PV maintenance cost in CHF/m² per year</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">M_ST,t</span><span class="var-desc">ST maintenance cost in CHF/m² per year</span></div>
    </div>
    <p>Solar thermal generation, usable heat, and residual heat demand:</p>
    <Formula label="Solar thermal generation">
      <code>ST_t      = y · q_ST · f_ST(t)             where f_ST(t) = max(0, 1 − (t−1) · d_ST)</code><br/>
      <code>ST_use,t  = ST_t · u_ST(y,t)               (usable solar thermal heat)</code><br/>
      <code>H_res,t   = max(0, Q_current − ST_use,t)   (residual heat demand)</code>
    </Formula>
    <div class="var-list">
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">q_ST</span><span class="var-desc">Specific annual ST yield, kWh/(m²·year)</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">d_ST</span><span class="var-desc">Annual ST degradation rate</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">u_ST(y,t)</span><span class="var-desc">ST utilisation factor in year t (see section J)</span></div>
    </div>
    <p>Total scenario cost (present value) including initial investment I₀:</p>
    <Formula label="Total scenario cost (present value)">
      <code>K_Scenario,Total = I₀ + Σ [ K_Scenario,t / (1 + i)^t ]  for t = 1…N</code><br/>
      <code>I₀ = Inv_PV · x + Inv_ST · y + K_Batt</code>
    </Formula>
    <p>Annual scenario emissions:</p>
    <Formula label="Annual scenario emissions">
      <code>E_Scenario,t = S_res,t · EF_electricity + H_res,t · EF_heat
                  + PV_t · EF_PV + ST_t · EF_ST</code>
    </Formula>
    <div class="var-list">
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">EF_PV</span><span class="var-desc">Lifecycle emission factor of PV generation (kg CO₂/kWh)</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">EF_ST</span><span class="var-desc">Lifecycle emission factor of ST generation (kg CO₂/kWh)</span></div>
    </div>
    <p>Cumulative scenario emissions:</p>
    <Formula label="Cumulative scenario emissions">
      <code>E_Scenario,Total = Σ E_Scenario,t  for t = 1…N</code>
    </Formula>
  </Section>

  <Section chip="06 / H" label="H · Inflation" title="Inflation Assumption" id="s-6-h">
    <p>An annual inflation factor can be enabled in the model. If activated, annual costs electricity prices, heating prices, fixed electricity charges, and maintenance costs increase each year by the specified percentage. The <strong>feed-in tariff remains constant</strong>, as it is assumed to be contractually fixed with the grid operator. Initial investments are also not adjusted for inflation, as they are incurred at the start of the project.</p>
  </Section>

  <Section chip="06 / I" label="I · Utilisation" title="Utilisation Rates and Self-Consumption" id="s-6-i">
    <p>For photovoltaic systems, not all generated electricity can be used directly in the town hall. The <strong>self-consumption rate sc(x,t)</strong> describes what proportion of PV output in year t is used on-site. As PV area increases, this proportion tends to decrease because production more often exceeds current electricity demand. If a battery is activated, the self-consumption share can increase, as part of the excess PV electricity can be temporarily stored and used later. The value is bounded between 0 and 1.</p>
    <p>For solar thermal energy, not all generated heat can be fully utilised. The <strong>utilisation factor u_ST(y,t)</strong> describes the proportion of solar thermal production that can actually meet heat demand. For small solar thermal areas, a high utilisation rate is assumed; for larger areas, the usable portion decreases because more heat is produced than can be directly used or stored. This factor is also bounded between 0 and 1.</p>
    <p>These dynamic rates are essential for the validity of the optimisation model. Without them, the solver would assume an unrealistic linear scalability of yields and would theoretically over-engineer the roof with solar components, since every additional square metre would produce a proportional benefit. The degressively decreasing factors model the real-world phenomenon of temporary surplus production, forcing the model to balance the marginal costs of additional area against its diminishing marginal benefit.</p>
  </Section>

  <Section chip="06 / J" label="J · Formal" title="Formal Representation of Utilisation Rates" id="s-6-j">
    <p>For photovoltaics, the self-consumption rate sc(x,t) is modelled as an area-dependent function. <em>sc_Slider</em> is the reference self-consumption rate assumed when the PV system covers the entire available roof area A_Roof. When the battery option is activated, the dummy variable <em>ActiveBatt</em> jumps from 0 to 1:</p>
    <Formula label="PV self-consumption rate">
      <code>sc(x,t) = max(0, min(1,  1 − (1 − sc_Slider) · x/A_Roof
              + ActiveBatt · min(0.5, γ · q_PV · B_estimate · f_Batt(t) / x)  ))</code>
    </Formula>
    <p>The remaining usable battery capacity in year t is described by the degradation factor:</p>
    <Formula label="Battery degradation factor">
      <code>f_Batt(t) = max(0, 1 − (t−1) · d_Batt)</code>
    </Formula>
    <div class="var-list">
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">d_Batt</span><span class="var-desc">Battery annual degradation rate (% capacity lost per year)</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">γ</span><span class="var-desc">Calibration factor for battery effect on self-consumption (0 – 1)</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">ActiveBatt</span><span class="var-desc">Battery activation dummy (0 = off, 1 = on)</span></div>
    </div>
    <p>The estimated battery capacity B_estimate is derived from the battery cost entered, using a piecewise cost-to-capacity function:</p>
    <Formula label="Battery capacity estimate (piecewise)">
      <code>B_estimate(K_Batt) =
  K_Batt / 847                          if K_Batt &lt; 16,940 CHF
  20 + (K_Batt − 16,940) / 163.25      if 16,940 ≤ K_Batt &lt; 30,000 CHF
  100 + (K_Batt − 30,000) / 266.67     if K_Batt ≥ 30,000 CHF</code>
    </Formula>
    <p>For solar thermal systems, the utilisation factor u_ST(y,t) is modelled as an area-dependent function. <em>u_min</em> is the minimum utilisation rate when the full roof area A_Roof is used for solar thermal. First, the effective ST area in year t (accounting for degradation) is calculated:</p>
    <Formula label="Effective ST area">
      <code>y_eff(t) = y · f_ST(t)</code>
    </Formula>
    <p>The solar thermal utilisation factor then follows:</p>
    <Formula label="ST utilisation factor">
      <code>u_ST(y,t) = max(u_min, min(1,  1 − (1 − u_min) · (y_eff(t) − 1) / (A_Roof − 1)  ))</code>
    </Formula>
    <div class="var-list">
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">u_min</span><span class="var-desc">Minimum utilisation rate when full roof area is used for ST</span></div>
      <div class="var-row"><span class="var">A_Roof</span><span class="var-desc">Total available roof area (m²)</span></div>
    </div>
    <p>For a solar thermal area of 1 m², a full utilisation rate of 100 % is assumed. As the effective area grows, the factor decreases gradually until it reaches <em>u_min</em>, reflecting the fact that larger systems more frequently generate excess heat that cannot be fully utilised.</p>
  </Section>

  <!-- Embedded calculator -->
  <section class="embed">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="embed-head reveal">
        <span class="lbl">Live tool · interactive</span>
        <h2 class="serif">Try the calculator</h2>
        <p>The full interactive model. Adjust the PV and ST sliders to see how CO₂ savings, costs, payback period and NPV respond in real time.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="embed-frame reveal-scale">
        <iframe src="https://som-calculator.vercel.app" title="Rathaus Carbon Reduction Calculator" loading="lazy" allow="fullscreen"></iframe>
      </div>
      <div class="embed-foot">
        <a class="btn" href="https://som-calculator.vercel.app" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open in new tab ↗</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</Base>

<style is:global>
  .lead{
    padding:32px 0 16px;
    font-size:clamp(16px, 1.8vw, 19px);
    line-height:1.75;
    color:var(--ink-soft);
    max-width:74ch;
    font-weight:300;
  }
  .lead em{font-style:italic;color:var(--ink)}

  .var-list{
    margin:16px 0 20px;
    max-width:74ch;
    border-top:1px solid var(--line);
  }
  .var-row{
    display:grid;
    grid-template-columns:110px 1fr;
    gap:12px;
    padding:10px 0;
    border-bottom:1px solid var(--line);
    align-items:baseline;
  }
  .var{
    font-family:'JetBrains Mono','Fira Mono',monospace;
    font-size:13px;
    color:var(--moss);
    font-weight:500;
    letter-spacing:0.02em;
  }
  .var-desc{
    font-size:14.5px;
    color:var(--ink-soft);
    line-height:1.65;
    font-weight:300;
  }
  .lead strong{font-weight:500;color:var(--ink)}
  .lead-sub{
    padding:0 0 16px;
    font-size:clamp(15px, 1.6vw, 17px);
    line-height:1.8;
    color:var(--ink-soft);
    max-width:74ch;
    font-weight:300;
    margin-top:-8px;
  }
  .lead-cta{
    margin:4px 0 32px;
  }
  .cta-btn{
    display:inline-block;
    padding:13px 28px;
    background:var(--moss);
    color:#fff;
    font-size:13px;
    letter-spacing:.16em;
    text-transform:uppercase;
    font-weight:500;
    border-radius:2px;
    transition: background 0.25s var(--ease-out), transform 0.25s var(--ease-out);
  }
  .cta-btn:hover{
    background:var(--ink);
    transform:translateY(-2px);
  }
  .use-case-box{
    margin:8px 0 40px;
    padding:24px 28px;
    max-width:74ch;
    border:1px solid rgba(230,224,210,0.8);
    border-left:3px solid var(--moss);
    border-radius:2px;
    background:rgba(59,90,63,0.04);
  }
  .use-case-label{
    display:block;
    font-size:11px;
    letter-spacing:.22em;
    text-transform:uppercase;
    color:var(--moss);
    font-weight:600;
    margin-bottom:10px;
  }
  .use-case-box p{
    margin:0;
    font-size:clamp(14.5px, 1.5vw, 16px);
    line-height:1.75;
    color:var(--ink-soft);
    font-weight:300;
  }

  .metrics{
    display:grid;
    grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fit, minmax(220px, 1fr));
    margin:28px 0 6px;
    border-top:1px solid var(--line);
    border-bottom:1px solid var(--line);
    max-width: 90ch;
  }
  .metric{
    padding:24px 22px;
    border-right:1px solid var(--line);
    border-bottom:1px solid var(--line);
    transition: background 0.3s var(--ease-out);
  }
  .metric:hover{background:var(--sand)}
  .metric .name{
    font-size:11px;
    letter-spacing:.18em;
    text-transform:uppercase;
    color:var(--moss);
    font-weight:600;
    margin-bottom:10px;
  }
  .metric .desc{
    font-size:14px;
    color:var(--ink-soft);
    line-height:1.65;
  }

  .embed{
    background: var(--ink);
    color: var(--paper);
    padding: clamp(64px, 9vw, 100px) 0;
    margin-top: 48px;
  }
  .embed-head{
    margin-bottom: 32px;
  }
  .embed .lbl{
    font-size:11px;
    letter-spacing:.32em;
    text-transform:uppercase;
    color:var(--accent);
    font-weight:500;
  }
  .embed h2{
    font-size:clamp(28px, 4vw, 44px);
    line-height:1.1;
    font-weight:400;
    margin:14px 0 16px;
